Introduction

In this homework quarterly gasoline and diesel sales (in 1000 m3) of a major distributor between 2000 and 2006 is analyzed and then, the relationship of this data with another number of potential independent variable is investigated.

##Data prepartion

Before going into analyzing part, the data is prepared. Firstly all the variable types are set to numeric, then the columns are renamed. After these steps, the date column is added in quarters and first column is deleted.

gasoline1 <- read_csv("IE360_Spring22_HW2_data.csv", 
    col_types = cols(Quarter = col_number(), 
        `Unleaded Gasoline Sale (UGS)` = col_number(), 
        RNUV = col_number(), `Price of Unleaded Gasoline (PU)` = col_number(), 
        `Price of Diesel Gasoline (PG)` = col_number(), 
        `# of Diesel Gasoline Vehicles (NDGV)` = col_number()))

gasoline<-gasoline1[,-1]


gasoline<- gasoline[-c(29:32),]
gasoline<-gasoline%>%
  rename(
    UGS=`Unleaded Gasoline Sale (UGS)`,
    NLPG=`# LPG Vehicles (NLPG)`,
    PU= `Price of Unleaded Gasoline (PU)`,
    PG= `Price of Diesel Gasoline (PG)`,
    NUGV=`# Unleaded Gasoline Vehicles (NUGV)`,
    NDGV= `# of Diesel Gasoline Vehicles (NDGV)`,
    GNP_A= `GNP Agriculture`,
    GNP_C = `GNP Commerce`,
    GNP_T= `GNP Total`
  )
    gasoline$NLPG<-str_replace_all(gasoline$NLPG, fixed(" "), "")
    gasoline$NUGV<-str_replace_all(gasoline$NUGV, fixed(" "), "")
    gasoline$GNP_A<-str_replace_all(gasoline$GNP_A, fixed(" "), "")
    gasoline$GNP_C<-str_replace_all(gasoline$GNP_C, fixed(" "), "")
    gasoline$GNP_T<-str_replace_all(gasoline$GNP_T, fixed(" "), "")
    gasoline$NLPG<-as.numeric(gasoline$NLPG)
    gasoline$NUGV<-as.numeric(gasoline$NUGV)
    gasoline$GNP_A<-as.numeric(gasoline$GNP_A)
    gasoline$GNP_C<-as.numeric(gasoline$GNP_C)
    gasoline$GNP_T<-as.numeric(gasoline$GNP_T)
    date = c("2000-01-01", "2000-04-01", "2000-08-01", "2000-12-01",
             "2001-01-01", "2001-04-01", "2001-08-01", "2001-12-01",
             "2002-01-01", "2002-04-01", "2002-08-01", "2002-12-01",
             "2003-01-01", "2003-04-01", "2003-08-01", "2003-12-01",
             "2004-01-01", "2004-04-01", "2004-08-01", "2004-12-01",
             "2005-01-01", "2005-04-01", "2005-08-01", "2005-12-01",
             "2006-01-01", "2006-04-01", "2006-08-01", "2006-12-01"
             )

    date=as.yearqtr(date, format= "%Y-%m-%d")

    gasoline$date= date

##Data Visualization

From the graph it can be understood that there is an decreasing trend. Also, the varience is relatively smaller in the middle.

   ggplot(gasoline,aes(x=date,y=UGS))+
      geom_line()+
      labs(x="Date",
           y="UGS",
           title="UGS for every Quater",
           subtitle="Over the years between 2000-2006")

To analyze the trend and also other time series components, the datats is created and then decomposed. It can be easily seen that the data is not stationary and also there is an seasonal effect in q3 in every year.Because of this reasons trend component is added to model.

datats <- ts(gasoline$UGS,freq=4,start=c(2000,1))
decomposed_data <- decompose(datats, "additive")
plot(decomposed_data)

gasoline$trend=c(1:28)
Q=seq(1,4,by=1)
gasoline=cbind(gasoline,Q)

##Analyzing Autocorrelation

The most important lag is lag 1. Then lag 4 and lag8. This decreasing lags is a sign of seasonality. Then lag columns are added to model.

acf(gasoline$UGS)

gasoline<-gasoline%>%
  mutate(lag4=lag(UGS,4),
         lag1=lag(UGS,1),
         lag8=lag(UGS,8))

##Fitting the Model

For the first model, only trend variable is included. The aim is to achieve residual with mean 0 and constant varience.
